Code 
# Part 3
#Making Graph
import plotnine as pt


breaks_labs= [500,1000,2000,4000,8000,16000,32000,64000]
labels_labs = ['500','1000','2000','4000','8000','16k','32k','64k']


(
pt.ggplot(filenew, pt.aes(x= "income", y = "life_exp", fill = "four_regions", size = "population"))
+pt.geom_point()
+pt.scale_fill_manual(values=["aqua","limegreen","red","yellow"])
+pt.labs(
    title = 'Life Expectancy and Income based on Region and Population',
    x = "Income",
    y= "Life Expectancy",
    fill = "World Regions",
    size = "Population"
)
+pt.scale_x_continuous(trans = 'log10',
breaks = breaks_labs,
labels = labels_labs,
limits = (500,100000)
)
+pt.scale_y_continuous(breaks = [20,30,40,50,60,70,80,90],
labels = ['20','30','40','50','60','70','80','90'],
limits= (20,90))
+pt.theme_light()
+ pt.annotate("text", x=6000, y=50, label="2010", size=100, alpha = .1)
)
/opt/anaconda3/lib/python3.12/site-packages/plotnine/layer.py:364: PlotnineWarning: geom_point : Removed 1 rows containing missing values.

#Part 4
breaks_labs= [500,1000,2000,4000,8000,16000,32000,64000]
labels_labs = ['500','1000','2000','4000','8000','16k','32k','64k']


(
pt.ggplot(filenew, pt.aes(x= "income", y = "life_exp", fill = "four_regions"))
+pt.geom_boxplot()
+pt.scale_fill_manual(values=["aqua","limegreen","red","yellow"])
+pt.labs(
    title = 'Life Expectancy and Income based on Region and Population',
    x = "Income",
    y= "Life Expectancy",
    fill = "World Regions",
    size = "Population"
)
+pt.theme_light()
)

Using geom_boxplot is useful for seeing an average of each of the regions and how they compare to each other. On the downside, there is not data for every country, and we cant see a difference in populations.

Question 2

Part 1: Here, we have exports as our x variable and income as the y. The colors are filtered by world region, and the bubble size is based on energy.

Code 
# Part 2
file2 = pd.read_csv("Data/q2data.csv")
file2

filenew2 =  file2.dropna()
filenew2['energy'] = pd.to_numeric(filenew2['energy'], errors='coerce')
Code 
# Part 3
(pt.ggplot(filenew2, pt.aes(x="exports",y="imports",fill = "four_regions", size = "energy"))
+pt.geom_point()
+pt.labs(
    title = 'Imports and Exports based on different Regions and Energy Usage',
    x = "Exports",
    y= "Imports",
    fill = "World Regions",
    size = "Energy"
)
+pt.scale_fill_manual(values=["aqua","limegreen","red","yellow"])
+pt.scale_y_continuous(breaks = [50,100,150,200,250,300,350,400],
labels = ['50','100','150','200','250','300','350','400'],
limits= (0,400))
+pt.scale_x_continuous(
breaks = [20,40,60,80,100,120,140,160,180,200,220],
labels = ['20','40','60','80','100','120','140','160','180','200','220'],
limits = (10,220)
)
+pt.theme_light()
+ pt.annotate("text", x=110, y=200, label="1997", size=100, alpha = .1)
)
/opt/anaconda3/lib/python3.12/site-packages/plotnine/layer.py:364: PlotnineWarning: geom_point : Removed 6 rows containing missing values.
Code 
#Part 4
(pt.ggplot(filenew2, pt.aes(x="exports",y="imports",group = "four_regions", color = "four_regions", size = "energy"))
+pt.geom_line(size = 0.5)
+pt.labs(
    title = 'Imports and Exports based on different Regions and Energy Usage',
    x = "Exports",
    y= "Imports",
    fill = "World Regions",
    size = "Energy"
)
+pt.scale_color_manual(values=["aqua","limegreen","red","yellow"])
 +pt.theme_light()
)

This plot does an okay job of showing the general trends that imports increase as exports increase. However, it is far too cluttered to see real trends, there are no individual data points, and we also cant factor in energy size.
